'''Samantha Jamie Bee''' (born October 25, 1969)<ref name="bio" /><ref name="TCE" /> is a Canadian-American comedian, writer, producer, political commentator, actress, and television host. Bee rose to fame as a correspondent on ''[[The Daily Show|The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'', where she became the longest-serving regular correspondent.<ref name="alumni" /> In 2015, she departed the show after 12 years to start her own show, ''[[Full Frontal with Samantha Bee]]''.

Bee became a US citizen in 2014, while retaining her Canadian citizenship. In 2017, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named her one of the 100 most influential people in the world on their annual [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] list.

==Early life and education==
Bee was born in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], the daughter of Debra and Ronald Bee.<ref name="book" /> She has said of her family: "Dating from well before the turn of the 20th century, if there has ever been a successful, happy marriage in my family lineage, I've yet to hear about it."<ref name="Fresh Air">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=127217785|title=The Not-So-Secret Life Of Samantha Bee|date=June 2, 2010|publisher=[[NPR]]|work=Fresh Air|accessdate=November 1, 2010}}</ref> Bee's parents split up soon after her birth, and she was initially raised by her grandmother, who worked as a secretary at the Catholic school Bee attended,<ref name="Crashed">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/features/how-samantha-bee-crashed-the-late-night-boys-club-20160630|title=How Samantha Bee Crashed the Late-Night Boys' Club|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 30, 2016|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref> on [[Roncesvalles Avenue]] during her childhood. She attended [[Humberside Collegiate Institute]] and [[York Memorial Collegiate Institute]].<ref name=TorontoStar>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/stage/2009/10/10/samantha_bee_a_beeautiful_life.html|title=Samantha Bee: A Bee-autiful Life|last=Ouzounian|first=Richard|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=October 10, 2009|accessdate=March 21, 2015}}</ref>

After graduating from high school, Bee attended [[McGill University]], where she studied humanities. Dissatisfied with a range of issues at the school, she transferred to the [[University of Ottawa]] after her first year. At the University of Ottawa, Bee signed up for a theatre class thinking it would be easy. The class led to Bee discovering her love of performing.<ref name="bio">{{cite web|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/BiographiesDetailsPage/BiographiesDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&display-query=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Biographies&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1650004669&source=Bookmark&u=mlin_b_northest&jsid=3de1204273193c50638555a32fe31d7b|title=Samantha Bee|publisher=Biography in Context {{subscription required}}|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Crashed" /> Bee later enrolled in the [[George Brown Theatre School]] in Toronto.<ref name="TorontoStar" />

==Career==

===Career beginnings===
Bee started auditioning for acting roles in Toronto while working as a waitress.<ref name="Crashed" /> At age 26, Bee toured with a stage production of ''[[Sailor Moon]]'' where she played the titular role.<ref name="Crashed" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Daily Show's Bee helps keep Canada in the "news": However, correspondent does not hide her past as Sailor Moon at the CNE|last=Wyatt|first=Nelson|date=July 22, 2005|work=[[Edmonton Journal]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}} (754 words)</ref> Bee performed in Sailor Moon's "A" cast and future husband [[Jason Jones (actor)|Jason Jones]] was a member of the "B" cast.<ref name="Crashed" />

Bee was one of the four founding members of Toronto-based [[sketch comedy]] troupe The Atomic Fireballs.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2016/07/28/toronto-native-samantha-bee-has-a-message-for-unhappy-americans-canada-is-full.html|title=Toronto native Samantha Bee has a message for unhappy Americans: 'Canada is full'|last=Sullivan|first=Margaret|date=July 28, 2016|website=thestar.com|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=July 28, 2016}}</ref> The Fireballs were all women. Demonstrating mutual support, the group would try to perform as many of each other's ideas as they could.<ref name="Smirking">{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/01/samantha-bee-full-frontal-c-v-r.html#|title=Smirking in the Boys' Room with Samantha Bee|last=Taister|first=Rebecca|date=January 26, 2016|work=The Cut|publisher=New York Media, LLC|access-date=December 28, 2016}}</ref>

===2003–2014: ''The Daily Show''===
Bee became a correspondent for ''[[Daily Show|The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'' on July 10, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/thu-july-10-2003/bee-white-house-uranium-admission|title=Bee White House Uranium Admission|work=The Daily Show with Jon Stewart|publisher=[[Comedy Central]]|date=July 10, 2003|accessdate=December 24, 2013}}</ref> Bee was the sole female correspondent on ''The Daily Show'' from her debut in 2003 until [[Kristen Schaal]] joined the show in March 2008. She was ''The Daily Show''{{'}}s first non-US citizen correspondent.<ref name=Cracked>{{cite news|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_15338_an-interview-with-3Ci3Ethe-daily-show3Ci3Es-samantha-bee.html|title=An interview with The Daily Show's Samantha Bee|first=Jeffrey|last=Felshman|work=[[Cracked.com]]|date=April 26, 2007|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> On that program, Bee demonstrated an ability to coax people into caricaturing themselves—particularly in segments like "Kill Drill", on hunters and [[fossil fuel]] executives claiming to be [[environmentalist]]s;<ref>{{cite web|title=Kill Drill|url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/ag8ezh/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-kill-drill|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref> "They So Horny?",<ref>{{cite web|title=They So Horny?|url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/b97ic9/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-they-so-horny-|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref> on the dearth of [[Asian people|Asian]] men in [[U.S. pornography]]; "Tropical Repression", on Ed Heeney, a [[Florida]] politician running his campaign based on [[opposition to gay rights]];<ref>[http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=128868&title=tropical-repression Tropical Repression], video aired August 2, 2004. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307161535/http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=128868&title=tropical-repression|date=March 7, 2008 }}</ref> "The Undecided", an over-the-top look at the undecided voters leading up to the [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004 US presidential elections]]; the "Samantha Bee's So You Want To Bee A..." report series, which humorously caricatured the way in which one can easily obtain a certain job, like becoming a [[527 group]]; and a segment entitled "NILFs" ("News I'd Like to F#@k"), discussing the sexiness of [[news anchor]]s: "[[CNN]] has the wholesome girl-next-door NILFs, the kind you can bring home to meet your mother. [[MSNBC]] has the dirty-over-30 NILFs. [[Fox News|Fox]] has the filthy NILFs who will report anything. They're the ''[[Hustler]]'' of NILFs."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/nhw1i8/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-news-i-d-like-to-f--k|title=News I'd Like To F@#K|date=May 16, 2007|publisher=[[Comedy Central]]|work=The Daily Show with Jon Stewart|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406002315/http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=87155&title=news-id-like-to-f@#k|archivedate=April 6, 2008|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref>

She had her first starring role in a feature film in 2004 with the Canadian [[independent film]] ''[[Ham & Cheese]]'', co-written by her husband [[Jason Jones (actor)|Jason Jones]] and starring Canadian comics [[Scott Thompson (comedian)|Scott Thompson]] and [[Dave Foley]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/ham-cheese-1200534562/|title=Review: 'Ham & Cheese'|last=Eisner|first=Ken|date=March 12, 2004|newspaper=Variety|access-date=January 8, 2017}}</ref> The film marked Bee's first starring role.<ref name="Rise and Rise">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/02/samantha-bee-timeline.html|title=The Rise and Rise of Samantha Bee|last=Duca|first=Lauren|date=February 8, 2016|work=Vulture|access-date=January 10, 2016}}</ref> She won a [[Canadian Comedy Awards|Canadian Comedy Award]] for "Pretty Funny Female Performance" for her role.<ref name="Rise and Rise" /> Jones joined ''The Daily Show'' as a correspondent in 2005, two years after his wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/samantha-bee-joins-the-late-night-boys-club/|title=Samantha Bee joins the late-night boys' club|date=January 31, 2016|work=CBS News|access-date=January 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name="For Two">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950CE1D6123EF930A25752C1A9639C8B63|title=A night out with: Samantha Bee; Joking for Two|last=Miller|first=Winter|date=November 13, 2005|newspaper=The New York Times|edition=online|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Jones became a freelance correspondent for the show while Bee reduced her workload during her [[pregnancy]].<ref name="For Two" />

[[File:SamanthaBeeFeb2011.jpg|upright|thumb|Bee at a [[Hudson Union Society]] event, 2011]]
In December 2005, on ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'', [[Bill O'Reilly (commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] used a clip of Bee from ''The Daily Show'' as an example of "[[Secularization of Christmas#2004-2005 Fox News campaign|The War on Christmas]]", presenting it as having aired recently. The satirical clip featured Bee mentioning how [[Christmas]] was the only religious holiday that's also a [[Federal holidays in the United States|federal holiday in the United States]], with O'Reilly talking about "[[Secularity|Secular]] Central...excuse me, Comedy Central".<ref>''The O'Reilly Factor'', Fox News Channel, December 2, 2005.</ref><ref>''The Radio Factor with Bill O'Reilly'', December 2, 2005.</ref> [[Jon Stewart]] responded on his show; inviting Bee out for a discussion, and unlike in the clip that aired on ''Factor'', Bee was visibly eight months pregnant. Bee joked it was obvious that the footage O'Reilly showed was a year old (it originally aired in 2004) because she had different highlights in her hair, before stating that her water had just broken.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/wed-december-7-2005/headlines---secular-central|title= Secular Central|date=December 7, 2005|work=The Daily Show with Jon Stewart|publisher=[[Comedy Central]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101110144957/http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/wed-december-7-2005/headlines---secular-central|archivedate=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Rise and Rise" /> Bee was recognized with a 2005 [[Canadian Comedy Award]] for Best Female TV Performance for her work on ''The Daily Show''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our 2005 Canadian Comedy Award recipients|url=http://www.canadiancomedy.ca/awardwinners.php?year=2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211223434/http://www.canadiancomedy.ca/awardwinners.php?year=2005|dead-url=yes|archive-date=February 11, 2016|website=Canadian Comedy Awards|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>

On January 20, 2008, Bee finished as the highest scoring celebrity in the [[CBC Television|CBC]] game show ''[[Test The Nation]]''. She had a minor role in Episode 15, "[[List of Little Mosque on the Prairie episodes#Season 2 (2007/08)|Spy Something or Get Out]]", of ''[[Little Mosque on the Prairie]]''. Bee also appeared in the 12th episode of [[List of Law & Order episodes (season 20)|Season 20]] of ''[[Law & Order]]'' ("[[Blackmail (Law & Order episode)|Blackmail]]", episode 445), which aired on January 15, 2010. She played a minor role in an episode of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Bored to Death]]''. She appeared as herself on the "[[List of The Electric Company (2009 TV series) episodes#Season 2|Madame President]]" episode of [[The Electric Company (2009 TV series)|''The Electric Company'']]. Bee also did a guest voice role of a talk show hostess named Pam in the Season 2 finale of ''[[Bob's Burgers]]'', in addition to providing the voice for Lyla Lolliberry for two episodes in Season 4 of ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''. She appeared on ''[[Sesame Street]]'' during Season 42 as [[Mother Goose]].
In 2009, Bee appeared in the original cast of ''[[Love, Loss, and What I Wore]]''.<ref name=SA>{{cite web|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2009/10/02/theater/reviews/02love.html|title=Spandex Agonistes: Why Don't You Try It On?|accessdate=April 21, 2011|date=October 2, 2009|author=Isherwood, Charles|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> That same year, she had a small role in the comedy ''[[Whatever Works]]'', written and directed by [[Woody Allen]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ChristianAnswers.Net|url=http://www.christiananswers.net/spotlight/movies/2009/whateverworks2009.html|title=Whatever Works|author=Schumacher, Spencer}}</ref>

Bee authored the book ''I Know I Am, But What Are You?'',<ref name=book>{{cite book|title=I know I am, but what are you?|first=Samantha|last=Bee|oclc=419815571|isbn=978-1-4391-4273-8|year=2010}}</ref> which was published in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|first=Diedre|last=Donahue|title=Hot summer author: Samantha Bee|date=May 27, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2010-05-26-summer-bee_N.htm|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=June 10, 2010}}</ref> She became the longest-serving regular ''Daily Show'' correspondent after passing [[Stephen Colbert]]'s record in 2011.<ref name=alumni>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/31/entertainment/gallery/the-daily-show-famous-alumni/|title='The Daily Show's' famous alumni|work=[[CNN]]|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> The same year, Bee collaborated with her longtime friend [[Allana Harkin]] on the [[parenting blog]] "Eating Over the Sink" for the online magazine ''[[Babble.com|Babble]]''.<ref name=nymag>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/01/samantha-bee-full-frontal-c-v-r.html|title=Smirking in the Boys' Room with Samantha Bee|first=Rebecca|last=Traister|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> In 2012, she appeared in [[Ken Finkleman]]'s series ''[[Good God (TV series)|Good God]]'' as Shandy Sommers, a devoutly Christian [[cable news]] host. She has also played roles in the series ''[[Bounty Hunters (U.S. TV series)|Bounty Hunters]]'' and ''[[Game On (Canadian teen series)|Game On]]''. In 2014, Bee was a panellist on ''[[Canada Reads]]'', the CBC's annual national book debate. She defended [[Rawi Hage]]'s novel ''[[Cockroach (novel)|Cockroach]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Samantha Bee and Rawi Hage talk Canada Reads|url=http://www.cbc.ca/books/canadareads/2013/12/samantha-bee-and-rawi-hage-talk-canada-reads.html|work=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=December 12, 2013|accessdate=November 24, 2016}}</ref> On October 7, 2014, in the absence of [[Jon Stewart]], she co-hosted ''The Daily Show'' with Jones.<ref name=":0" />

===2015–present: ''Full Frontal with Samantha Bee''===
{{main|Full Frontal with Samantha Bee}}
In March 2015, it was announced that she would leave ''The Daily Show'' – after 12 years – to host her own satirical news show on [[Turner Broadcasting System|TBS]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/trending/samantha-bee-leaves-the-daily-show-to-start-her-own-satirical-news-program-1.2983660|title=Samantha Bee leaves The Daily Show to start her own satirical news program|first=Alexandra|last=Hunnings|work=[[CBC News]]|edition=online|date=March 5, 2015|publisher=CBC/Radio Canada|accessdate=November 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/09/02/samantha-bee-full-frontal-premiere-january-promo|title=Samantha Bee's Full Frontal to premiere in January |first=Ariana|last=Bacle|work=Entertainment Weekly|edition=online|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=November 21, 2015}}</ref> Bee departed ''The Daily Show'' on April 30, 2015.<ref>{{cite episode |series= The Daily Show |title= Thursday, April 30, 2015|airdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> Her new show, ''Full Frontal with Samantha Bee'', debuted on February 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/10/arts/television/review-full-frontal-with-samantha-bee.html|title=Review: Samantha Bee's Fierce, Fiery Feminism Anchors 'Full Frontal'|first=James|last=Poniewozik|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> With the program's debut, Bee became the first woman to host a late-night satire show.<ref name="Smirking" /> Bee also tried to implement a hiring process which would give her show a more diverse staff than what is typical for a late night comedy show.<ref name="Smirking" /> The first season of ''Full Frontal'' generated critical acclaim<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/full_frontal_with_samantha_bee/s01|title=Full Frontal with Samantha Bee: Season 1|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/full-frontal-with-samantha-bee|title=Full Frontal with Samantha Bee: Season 1|work=Metacritic|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> and in November 2016, the show was renewed for a second season throughout 2017.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TsovDxkIeKs|title=Real or Fake: Extra Special Announcement|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=Full Frontal with Samantha Bee|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>

Bee is an executive producer of the TBS comedy series ''[[The Detour (TV series)|The Detour]]'' (2016–present), which she created with her husband, [[Jason Jones (actor)|Jason Jones]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/04/jason-jones-samantha-bee-the-detour-renewed-season-3-tbs-1202076899/|title=Jason Jones & Samantha Bee's 'The Detour' Renewed For Season 3 By TBS|last=Petski|first=Denise|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 25, 2017|accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref> One year into Bee's run on ''Full Frontal'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named Bee one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/collection/2017-time-100/4742710/samantha-bee/|title=Samantha Bee|last=Curtin|first=Jane|date=April 20, 2017|access-date=April 21, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> On April 29, 2017, ''Full Frontal with Samantha Bee'' hosted "[[Not the White House Correspondents' Dinner]]" which aired on TBS the same evening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/30/entertainment/samantha-bee-not-the-white-house-correspondents-dinner/index.html|title=Samantha Bee is throwing her own party the same night as White House Correspondents' Dinner|last=Gonzalez|first=Sandra|website=CNN|date=January 30, 2017|access-date=January 30, 2017}}</ref> In July 2017, Bee's "[[Nasty woman|Nasty Woman]] Shirt" campaign raised over $1&nbsp;million for [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nasty-woman-emmy-nominee-samantha-bee-hits-1-million-goal-planned-parenthood-1020861|title='Nasty Woman' (and Emmy Nominee) Samantha Bee Hits $1 Million Goal for Planned Parenthood|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=July 13, 2017|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref> In January 2018, TBS renewed ''Full Frontal'' for a third and fourth season, set to air through 2020. Bee's deal with [[Turner Broadcasting System|Turner]] runs through 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/full-frontal-samantha-bee-renewed-2-more-seasons-at-tbs-1073891|title='Full Frontal With Samantha Bee' Renewed for Two More Seasons at TBS|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 11, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>

===="Feckless cunt" controversy====
In an episode of ''Full Frontal'' aired on May 30, 2018, Bee commented on a tweet that [[Ivanka Trump]] had posted of herself and her child: "You know, Ivanka, that's a beautiful photo of you and your child, but let me just say, one mother to another: Do something about your dad's immigration practices, you feckless cunt! He listens to you! Put on something tight and low-cut and tell your father to fuckin' stop it."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jezebel.com/all-of-our-favorite-conservatives-are-pissed-about-sama-1826453169|title=All of Our Favorite Conservatives Are Pissed About Samantha Bee Calling Ivanka a 'Feckless Cunt'|last=Lutkin|first=Aimée|date=May 31, 2018|work=[[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]]|access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref> The day after the segment aired, Bee apologized: "I would like to sincerely apologize to Ivanka Trump and to my viewers for using an expletive on my show to describe her last night. It was inappropriate and inexcusable. I crossed a line, and I deeply regret it."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/31/media/samantha-bee-apologizes-ivanka-trump/index.html|title=Samantha Bee apologizes for vulgar remark about Ivanka Trump: 'I crossed a line'|last=Pallotta|first=Frank|date=May 31, 2018|work=[[CNNMoney]]|access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref> In response to her comment, [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] posted on Twitter: "Why aren't they firing no talent Samantha Bee for the horrible language used on her low ratings show? A total double standard but that's O.K., we are Winning, and will be doing so for a long time to come!"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1002508937445478402|title=Donald J. Trump on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref>  [[Kathy Griffin]], [[Michelle Wolf]], [[Sarah Silverman]], and [[Jon Stewart]] defended Bee, with Stewart suggesting much of the outrage over the joke was strategic rather than genuine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/06/jon-stewart-samantha-bee-defense-michelle-wolf-the-break|title=Jon Stewart Doesn't Buy the Outrage About Samantha Bee's Ivanka Trump Dig|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=June 4, 2018|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=June 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref> The show featured fewer national advertisements the following week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/samantha-bee-full-frontal-apology-sees-advertisers-pause-but-no-mass-withdrawal-1202405522/|title=Samantha Bee 'Full Frontal' Apology Sees Many Advertisers Hit Pause|last=Hayes|first=Dade|date=June 7, 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref> Bee began the episode with an apology to any women she had offended and lamenting that one bad word had overshadowed the policy of detaining migrant children which she had been criticizing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/samantha-bee-ivanka-trump-apology-feckless-donald-trump-immigration-full-frontal-tbs-video-1202404885/|title=Samantha Bee Apologizes Defiantly For Last Week's First-Daughter Slur On 'Full Frontal'|last=Moraes|first=Lisa de|date=June 7, 2018|work=Deadline|access-date=June 8, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-samantha-bee-20180606-story.html|title=Samantha Bee apologizes and lashes back at her critics on 'Full Frontal' over Ivanka Trump controversy|last=Ali|first=Lorraine|date=June 6, 2018|website=latimes.com|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref> Two weeks after Bee's original comment, Stephen Colbert ended a ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert|Late Show]]'' segment on border separations with "If we let this happen in our name, we are a feckless (pause) country."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/stephen-colbert-donald-trump-jeff-sessions-children-border-immigration-video-1202411206/|title=Stephen Colbert: “Feckless Country” Rips Children From Parents At Border|last= de Moraes |first= Lisa|date=June 15, 2018|website=deadline.com|access-date=July 28, 2018}}</ref>

==Influences==
Bee has credited [[Jon Stewart]] as one of her major influences,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-daily-show-comedians-who-got-their-start-2015-7|title=12 influential comedy careers Jon Stewart helped launch on 'The Daily Show'|work=[[Business Insider]]|author=Ian Phillips|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> and in several interviews she has said that her other comedic influences include [[Steve Martin]], [[David Letterman]], [[Mary Tyler Moore]], [[Lucille Ball]], [[Carol Burnett]], [[Betty White]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=UFwLpSel4kg|title=Samantha Bee comic influences|work=YouTube|date=June 6, 2010|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> and [[Joan Rivers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2016/feb/08/samantha-bee-full-frontal-comedy-im-the-only-woman-stupid-enough-to-do-this-job?|title=Samantha Bee: 'I'm the only woman stupid enough to do this job'|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Lorraine Berry|date=February 8, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In 2001, Bee married actor [[Jason Jones (actor)|Jason Jones]], whom she first met in 1996.<ref name="Crashed" /> They reside in [[Manhattan]], New York.<ref name=TVNR>{{cite web|url=http://tvnewsroom.org/biography-images/samantha-bee-3776/|title=Samantha Bee – Biography and Images|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> In January 2006, she gave birth to Piper Bee-Jones; she returned to ''[[The Daily Show]]'' in March 2006.<ref name="TVNR" /> On January 24, 2008, Bee announced a second pregnancy on air during a bit about the media's coverage of the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential campaign]].<ref>[http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=148479&title=daily-show-down Daily Show-Down], video aired January 24, 2008. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307011532/http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=148479&title=daily-show-down|date=March 7, 2008}}</ref> In 2008, their second child, Fletcher Bee-Jones, was born.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2010/12/01/samantha-bee-adjusts-to-her-party-of-five/|title=Samantha Bee adjusts to her party of five|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Their third child, a daughter named Ripley, was born in late 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/31/magazine/31FOB-Domains-t.html?_r=0|title=Samantha Bee's Laughing Pad|last=Lewine|first=Edward|date=October 28, 2010|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=November 21, 2015}}</ref> During her third pregnancy, Bee joked she and Jones were "just procreating like we're farmers."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/j7j50y/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-the-spilling-fields---vietnamese-fisherman|title=The Spilling Fields – Vietnamese Fisherman|date=June 3, 2010|work=[[Comedy Central]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>

Bee holds both Canadian and United States citizenship after being naturalized as an American citizen in 2014.<ref name="rs-over">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/samantha-bee-on-election-i-want-it-to-be-over-so-badly-w442956|title=Samantha Bee on 2016 Election: 'I Want It to Be Over So Badly'|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|date=October 1, 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=January 8, 2017|quote=this year's election marks the first time she and her husband, fellow former Daily Show correspondent Jason Jones, would be able to vote since they now have dual citizenship }}</ref><ref name="WP">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/samantha-bee-to-discontented-americans-canada-is-full/2016/07/27/25b7593a-5372-11e6-bbf5-957ad17b4385_story.html|title=Samantha Bee says her show isn't influential. Don't believe her.|first=Margaret|last=Sullivan|date=July 27, 2016|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 8, 2017|quote=Samantha Bee has been a United States citizen for only a couple of years}}</ref>

